text.tspan: Drought Severity Index, United States, 1895 to 2015
The Palmer Drought Severity Index is the most widely used index to measure drought severity over time. An index
value of zero represents the average moisture conditions observed between 1931 and 1990 at a given location. A
positive value means conditions are wetter than average, while a negative value is drier than average. A value
between -2 and -3 indicates moderate drought, -3 to -4 is severe drought, and -4 or below indicates extreme
Source: NOAA (National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration) via the US EPA
